{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_melville_ver02/data/sn84026749/00222254036/1923100201/0363.xml":{"full_text":"I\nJ ADVANCING WASHING.\nJi TON\u2019S INTERESTS\n'Hill STOCKS\nIUD DOLL\nMARKET\nIndustrial List Irregular But\nSeveral Specialty Stocks\nn Show Sharp Advances.\nNEW YORK, Oct. 2.\u2014The char-\nof trading In the first two\njfiOun on the stock exchange today\n\u25a0did not reveal much change from\nthat of several previous sessions.\nF There were a few sharp advances\nIn three or four specialties which\nare under pool control, such as\nDavidson Chemical, Liggett Myers\nand Mallinson, but the main groups\nqf stocks continued a purposeless\ncourse, although a tendency to re*\nsist professional pressure was again\nmuch in evidence. Reports pf the\nexistence of an unwieldy short in\nterest were freely circulated, which i\ntended to stay the hand of the bear\ntraders, tor the time being at least.\nAt the same time they'could not be\ncoerced into active covering, reason\ning that the immediate future had\nnothing tn store that could be cal-\nculated to lift the prevailing uncer-\nRailroad shares formed the only\nin which some degree of\nconstructive initiative was shown.\nLed .by Southern Railway, which\nwas boosted because of dividend pos\nsibilities. the whole low priced sec\ntion joined in a mildly bullish de-\nmonstration, which carried prices i\nfrom a fraction to a point above i\ntheir previous finals. Baltimore and\nOhio Was favored among the divi-\nWfcdend payers on the theory that the\n\u25a0present dividend warrants a higher j\nF gening price for the stock. Northern j\nI Pacific, however, was under pres-\nsure., i\nThe industrial list went through\nits customary backing and filling\nprocess, but the undertone was\nsteady. Stimulated by the firmness\nta the railroads, leading industrials\nturned upward, but the strength i\n*was only temporary, and in the\nsecond hour the main body of ctocks i\ntook a position fractionally above i\nyesterday\u2019s closing. Jones Tea,\nhowever, resumed its downward\ntrend, declining to 82% for a loss\nof hearly two points, and American\nWriting Paper preferred broke a\npoint to five following the announce-\nment of* the filing of a petition ask- 1\ning for the appointment of a re- J\ncelver.\nCan money renewed at 5% per J\neent, one quarter per cent above\nyesterday\u2019s renewal rate. 1\u2014\nI\nTELES COOLIDGE I\nI NO FfflU\nISNEEOEO\nV 1\nNational Grange Committee 1\nCalls at White House.\nViews of Members.\nThe executive committee of the\nMational Grange, summoned to the\nWhite House by President Coolidge,\nyesterday entered a strong plea 1\nagainst all proposals for the call ot\na special session of Congress to con-\naider agricultural legislation.\nThe committee also opposed price- j\nfixing for wheat and an increase ip\nthe tariff duty on wheat. The j\nreceommendation of Secretary Wai-\nlace for a Governmental marketing\norganisation was favored.\nThe grange committee was headed\nby S. J. Lowell, New York, master\nof the grange, and consisted of E.\nA. Eckert, Illinois, and Leslie R.\ngpmith, Massachusetts. Feeling that\n\u25a0Hie existing agricultural depression\n\u25a0te the result of purely economic\nconditions, the committee said that\nno immediate legislation could solve\nthe farm problem. 1\n\"With the exception of wheat\ngrowers, farmers generally through-\nout the country are enjoying a\n\u2022'favorable year,\u201d said Eckert. \"The\nneed of the wheat growers in the\nNorthwest is diversification of\n\"jJucb a change, however, would\nnot' be an Immediate cure and\nwould'. be expensive, because the\nNorthwest has been so long a one\ncrop territory that farmers there\npre not suitably, equipped to han\ndle anything but wheat.\u201d\nThe committee thought that farm\nconditions will adjust themselves\nsatisfactorily without the necessity\nfor any for-reaching plan of Gov\nernmental aid, other than through\nalready established agencies.\n1 W. B. HIBBS CO.\nF II\nMEMBERS\nI