52 251% <51% 253%\nOpen. High. Low. Close, i\nMoney on call.. 6% 5\nStock sates up to\u2014 j\nXI a. m. 12 noon. Ip.m. 2 p.m.\n182,100 279,'500\nBond sales up to\u2014 1\n11 a. m. 12 noon. Ip. m. 2p. m.\n4,048,000 6,467,000\nBENNING COUNCIL HOLDS\nANNUAL MEMORIAL RITES\nThe annual memorial services of j\nBenning Council, Junior. Order\nUnited American Mechanics, were 1\nheld last night in Odd Fellows Hall,\nBenning.\nJohn Prender, State council secre-\ntary, spoke on the history of the\norder. Addreses were made by the 1\nRev. Harry D. Mitchell and W. T.\nDouglass who presided. The invo-\nnation was made by the Rev. O. F.\nSherwood. Others who took part\nin the program were Wallace Carri-\ngan, Clinton Loretta and Ethel\nBrown;/ William F. Raymond,\nGeorge S. Wilson, John Prender,\nMrs. Charles Carrigan, C. W. Doug\nlass, R. R. Spelling, jJe Roy Taylor,\nW. H. Conklin, Frank Cooke and\nGeorge S. Wilson.\nThe memorial, committee included\nW. T. Douglass, chairman; P. N.\nMoulden, Lewis Gray, A. T. Gray,\nA. G. Ingles, L. G. Kirk, T. W.\nIngles, C. W. Douglass, secretary;\nA. E. Anderson, J. H. Ellis, H. A.\nDouglass, Lewis Milboume, F. D.\nCarrigan and G. W. Douglasg\nBISHOP SPURNS CZECHO\nSLOVAK PRESIDENT\nPRAGUE, Oct. 2.\u2014A Slovak\nbishop, who was refused a nassport\nto America recently by this gov\nernment because* he intended to\npropagate the policies of the Slo\nvak Separatist party, recently was\ninvited by President Masaryk to\nthe President\u2019s castle at Topolt\nchany, along with other Slovak\nbishops. He refused the invitation\nand telegraphed the President as\nfollows:\n\"Your government has hurt me\nto the quick and up to date has\nrefused to give me any satisfac\ntion. I, therefore, cannot ait at\nyour table.**\nTHEORY BANKS\nLOCK\u2019STRffT\u2019\n15 NIHH\nBrings Comfort to Bulls When\nOther Hopes Are\nUnavailing. x\nBy w. S. COUSINS,\n(Copyright. 143 R. by Cosmopolitan\nNews Service.)\nNEW YORK, Oct. 2.\u2014A widely\naccepted theory in the stock market\ntoday, partly a relic ofbygpne days,\nis that big Wall Street banks habi\ntually support the stock market\nwhenever it is exceptionally weak,\nor in danger of a bad break in\nprices.\nThe theory has brought some com\nfort to patient bulls, who have em\nbraced it when all -other hopes\nproved unavailing. It has been\ncited as the cause of many of the\nabrupt recoveries, and hailed as the\nnecessary prelude to the flotation of\nmany large issues of bonds and\npreferred stocks by the \"big in\nterests.\u201d\nConcerted support of speculative\nmarkets by banking institutions\nas such 'is largely a myth. The\nbank is a Commercial institution,\nthe activities of which are closely\ncircumscribed by national and State\nlaws. The amount- of bank funds\ntied up in investment stocks is\nnegligible.\nLooking for Bargains.\nWith, the banker himself, the\ncase is different. Usually a shrewd\njudge of security values, and wltn\na well-filled purse to back up his\njudgment, he is on the alert for\nbargains in securities. The end\nof every long decline in stock prices\nfinds him nibbling at good stocks\npriced low. Sometimes he works\nindependently, sometimes he forms\nan association with other bankers\nto purchase a block of stock suffi\ncient to give control of a corpo\nration.\nUnlike the speculator of small\nmteans, he relies on no brokerage\nservice to carry his stocks, but\nbuys them outright.\nIn some Instances, such as that\nof the Stutz Motor fiasco, and the\nSubmarine Boat change of owner\nship, a few rich bankers purchased\nsufficient stock to control the en\nterprise, conducting the business\nunder their own direction.\nNo Season In Market.\nBankers have been known to form\nprotective pools, with their personal\nfunds, halt a vicious attack on\nprices, which, carried to extreme,\nmight undermine public confidence\nin business generally. But such\nsupport is ephemeral In a few\ndays the purchased securities are\nfound trickling back to the market,\nhaving in the meantime sufficiently\nreduced the floating supply to help\nin stopping the run. r\nIt might be well to remember\nthat there is no season in the stock\nmarket. The proverbial, \"spring\nrise** seldojp materialises, and the\nautumn business revival, so often\nhailed as the big Incentive to a\nstock market rally, has been most\ndisappointing of late. The panic of\n1907 reached its culmination In the\nfall, and the most disastrous part\nof the 1920 decline came in Novem\nber and December. There are no\nprecedents in the stock market,\nsimilar events often prices\nentirely differently.\nTHREATS WITH HIS PISTOL\nBRING 360 DAYS IN JAIL\nA sentence of 360 days was\nmeted out to Walter Johnson,\ncolored, by Judge John P. McMahon\nin police court oday, for flourishing\na pistol. Policeman Schimkezy tes\ntified that he was standing at the\ncorner of Fifteenth and H streets\nnorthwest, when he saw an auto\nmobile approaching at a reckless\nspeed. It was followed by Sergeant\nEby, he said, and when it reached\nH street tried to turn west, but\nwas stopped 'by \u00abthe car platform\nThe policeman then jumped on the\nrunning board. The car was filled\nwith men and women and Johnson,\ntestimony showed, drew a .38 cali\nber revolver. threatening the police\nman. The pistol was not fired. A\nsearch of the automobile revealed\nanother .32 caliber automatic.\nALLEGED HANDBOOK\nOPERATOR ARRESTED\nGeorge Godfrey, who gave his ad\ndress as 461 G street northwest,\nand is said by police to\u2018stay at 62S\nE street northwest, was arrested\nlast night by Detectives Berry and\nMansfield, charged with violating\n\u25a0section 869 of the District of Co\nlumbia code, prohibiting taking bets\non hand book races. He was re\nleased on $2,000 bond.\nPolice say that Godfrey had been\ntaking bets from a number of wom\nen, one of whom won on a long\nshot, when Godfrey is said to have\n\"welched,\u201d declaring he did not get\nthe bet in time. The woman com\nplained and he was arrested on her\ninformation.\n11 HANDBOOK CASES\nCALLED FOR TRIAL\nThe Police Court docket for tomor\nrow contains the following handbook\ncases, posted today by Assistant Dis\ntrict\" Attorney David A. Hart, in\ncharge of prosecutions of violators of\nthe anti-gambling laws: Louis\nYoung and Harry Zeller, Louis\nYoung and Paul Figallo, David\nZerago and Paul Figallo, Harry\nZeller, Lloyd A. Nell, Frank Mc-\nCormick. Charles W. Onley and\nErnest F. Dorsey.\nThese cases are called for trial in\nthe United States branch of Police\nCourt.\nBARBER\u2019S FINGERS\nTORN IN ELECTRIC FAN\nHenry Melzer, who has scraped\nmany a man\u2019s physiognomy, suf\nfered a painful Injury last night in\nMiller\u2019s barber shop, just off Four\nteenth street and Pennsylvania ave\nnue, when he caught his fingers in\nan electric fan. Melzer was taken\nto the Emergency Hospital -and later\ntaken to his home.\nPhysicians say that one of his\nfingers is badly torn, but that it\nwill not be necessary to aniputate.it.\nI Curb Stocks.\n.bg R Hlbte 4 Cgl,\nv. Aak.\nAcme C0a1.........../.. 1% 2\nArkansas Nat. Gas S 5%\nBorden Co 116 120\nButte and Western..... 26 50\nCandelaria 6 6\nCarib Syndicate 3% 3%\nCar L. A P 1% 2\nCentrifugal Cast 1r0n... 19% 19%\nCities Service, new 13\u20194 13\nCities Service, old 129% 180%\nCities Service,\nDavis Daly 2% 2\nDubilier 9% 10%\nDurant of Delaware.... 29% 30\nDurant of Indiana 7% 8\nEngineers Petroleum.... 6 6\nEureka Cr0e5u5......... 7 9\nFederal 0i1........ 25 30\nFortuna Mining 6 8\nGiUette Safety Razon... 256 257\nGlen Alden Coal 70 76\nMlne\u00df H 13\nGoldfield Florence 58 60\nGoodyear T. AR. 10% 10%\nGulf OH of Penna....... 50% f.l\nHeyden Chemical 11%\n1 Hudson 0i1... 6 7\nIndependence Lead 19 23\nIntercom Rubber. 3% 3%\nInternet Petrol;, new... 15% 15%\nj Jerome Verde 1% 1%\nLyons Petroleums 55\n1 Mamoth Oil 5<\n1 Marland Oil of Mek.... 3% 8%\nMarlin Firearms 4%\nMason Valley.... 1% 2\nMesabi 5\nMexico OH. 56 61\nMountain Producers.... 14 14%\nMutual Oil 9% 9%\nX a\n1 Nevada Ophir 6 12\nNew Fiction Pub 1 8\n(New Cornelia.. 47% ig%\nNiplssing Mines 5% 5%\nOhio Copper 68 65\n1 Omar Oil 61 65\nPennock 0i1..... 11% 12\nPyrne Mfg. C 0... 9 9%\ni Radio, com... 8 3%\n\nSalt Creek, new.. 18 18?\nSapulpa, com 1% 1%\nl Southern Coal A 1r0n... 11 12\ni Softthern States 0i1.... 14% K\n1 Stutz Motors 11 13%\n1 Tidal Osage 6 9\n1 Tonopah Divide 82 34\n1 Tonopah Extension 2 2-A\nUnited Eastern 1% 1%\nUnited Prof, Shar. 5% 5%\nUnited Shoe Mach 35% 36%\n1 EM*\u00ae* Mach pf 25 26\nUnited- Verde 29% 30\nZ\nWest End Cons 75 79\nWilcox Oil A Ga 5...... 1% 4%\nYellow Taxi of N. Y.... 121 1128\nForeign Exchange.\nNEW YORK. Oct 2.\u2014Foreign\nexchange opening:\nDemand. Cables.\nSterling 84-53% $4.54\nit Francs .0594% .0595\n/Lire.... .0450% .0451\nJ %e1gian..0507% .0508\nCzechoslovak. K .0300 .0300%\nt Swiss .1783 .1785\nGui1der5......... .3927 .3930\nt Pesetas .1339 .1341\n\u25a0Sweden 2648 .2652\n-Norway 1581 .1585\nDenmark.. 1771 .1775\nMarks, 332,833,000 to a dollar.\nIPPOSCTIIf\nlIWI\nHI\nCongressman Hoch Sees No\nImmediate Relief for\nFarm Distress.\nWm \u2014a \u2014a wv-\nMIIaCaIMBwOIMU HcwS kMTTMws\nOpposition to all proposals to in-\nJ crease \u00a3he tariff duty on wheat to\nremedy fcrm ills was expressed to\nPresident Coolidge yesterday by Con\nj gressman 6och, of Kansas.\nThe present duty of 80 cento a\nbushel on wheat is fairly represen\n1, tative of the difference in cost of\nproduction here and Canada,\u201d said\nHoch, \"and if there is to he any\nchange in the Fordney-McCumber\nBill on this schedule it should be\n1 downward rather than upward.\n\"The root of the present farm dis\ntress is purely economic and lies\nin the disparity between what the\nfarmer receives for products he\nI sells for the material he buys. In\nthis situation po magic wand can\nbe waved to cure the trouble, which\nbest should be allowed to adjust It\nself through the natural course of\ndevelopment.\u201d\nand\n13 National Mortgage\n1| Investment Corporation gj\n811 Vermont Ave. N. W. Wfl\n|i Deals in the Best Real |||L\n|mL Estate Securities |w\u2019\nFirst and Second Trust Notes HP\nand Warehouse Receipts\nAre Purchased at Fair Rates\n111I 11 x 7% First Mortgage Notes\nE' SECURED by Improved District of\nColumbia Real Estate, are a GOOD\nft INVESTMENT. Offered in denomi- g|g?\nnations from $250 UP. Whb\nLATEST NEWS OF\nFINANCIAL WORLD\nTH Ti\nINWEST\ntenth Reserve Districf\u00dfepcrt\nShows Good Business Con\nditions Existing.\nCesmepoUiMi News Swvtse,\nImproved conditions in the Tenth\nFederal Reserve District, compris\ning the States of Kansas, Okla\nhoma, Colorado, Wyoming and\nNebraska, are reflected in the re\nport of the Kansas City Reserve\nRank.\nThe report says: \"Improvement\nin the economic position of the\nagricultural and livestock interests\nin evidence at this time tn all\nsections of the district. Advances\nIn prices of farm products and\nmeat animals to levels above those\nof a year ago and an enormous in\nflow of money from the marketing\nof these products of farm and\nrange are factors which have also\nhelped along this improvement.\u201d\nDeposits in savings banks In\ncreased 10.5 per cent over Septem\nber of last year, with fewer busi\nness failures involving smaller\nliabilities, the report also *ays.\nSome of the other features of the\nreport are: Heavily increased meat\npacking; a new high record in soft.\ncoal production was made; the sup\nply of' common labor is etlU in\nsufficient, to meet demand; building\nfleet a marked falling off in esti\nmated cost of construction.\nhmmi\nISKSW\n.llJMllir\nBen W. Hooper Lays Proposal\nBefore President\nRecommendations for amend\nments to the Transportation (Each-\nCummins) Act of 1620 to strengthen\nthe powers of the United Staters\nRailroad Labor board in enforcing\nits decisions were laid before Pres\ndent Coolidge at the White House\nyesterday by Ben W. Hooper, chair\nman of the Board.\nHooper said the proposed amend\nments were aimed to'put teeth into\nthe provisions of the law so that\nthe board could compel both the\nrailroad executives and the workers\nto respect and obey its rulings.\nThe proposals, he explained, were\nmade by him personally and did not\ncome officially from the board.\nForeign Bonds.\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs A Co.)\nFrench 4\u2019s 38%\nFrench s\u2019s 47\nPremium s\u2019B 57\nBritish Victory 4\u2019s 432\nNational War Loan s\u2019s 497\nWar Loan s\u2019s i 477\nItalian Notes, 1925 48\nItalian s\u2019s 42%\nBelgian Restoration 5\u20198....... 46\nPremium s\u2019s 49\n|\u201cWE BUY. SELL AND QUOTE~\nWWevCW DWvMj wwwww t\nCALL.\nRIEMER CO.\nHOME FURNITURE\nLOANS\nREML ESTATE\nFrom SSO to S3OO\nCOMMERCIAL LOAN\nAND FINANCE CORP. 11l\nR<wm 2il Bt N\n21","height":"26961","width":"22545"}}
